\\\n\\\\\\\\n---\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### SUMMARY\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI read all 10 files in scope (3 Java source files, 2 pom.xml files, 1 SPI services file, 1 Dockerfile, 1 docker-compose.yml, 1 frontend composable, and CHANGELOG.md) and performed a 6-item code quality review. I found **3 issues**: the Dockerfile references a jar file (`keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar`) that does not exist in the `docker/keycloak/` directory; the frontend `useAuth.js` hard-codes a production `auth.wotbtools.com` URL which prevents local development; and the `JuheQqIdentityProvider` logs `social_uid` length info that could be considered a minor information leak. The other known-good properties (APPKEY not hard-coded, no sensitive logging, JDK 21 HttpClient, final locals/params, error handling coverage, non-sensitive logging) are confirmed.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### EVIDENCE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n- **Item 1 — Sensitive information protection (APPKEY not hard-coded, not logged)**: CONFIRMED PASS. `JuheQqIdentityProviderConfig.java:21-22` — APPKEY is a configuration property retrieved via `getConfig().get(CONFIG_APPKEY)`, not hard-coded. `JuheQqIdentityProviderFactory.java:38` — `appkey.setSecret(true)` marks it as secret in Keycloak admin UI. `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:48-49` — on missing config, logs only \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"provider not fully configured\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", never the value. `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:82-83` and `149-151` — logs `code` and `type` only, never appkey or full URL.\\\\\\\\n- **Item 2 — JDK 21 java.net.http.HttpClient**: CONFIRMED PASS. `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:31-33` — uses `HttpClient.newBuilder()` with `connectTimeout`. `performLogin` at line 64-70 and `callback` at line 131-137 use `HttpRequest.newBuilder()` and `HTTP.send()`. Confirmed by `java/pom.xml:30` `<maven.compiler.release>21</maven.compiler.release>`.\\\\\\\\n- **Item 3 — All local variables and method parameters use `final`**: CONFIRMED PASS. Every method parameter in all three Java files uses `final` (e.g.,