    \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"result\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Now I have a comprehensive view of all the files. Let me assemble my 6-item checklist review.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nHere is the complete structured report based on my thorough reading of all files in scope.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n---\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### SUMMARY\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nI read all 10 files in scope (3 Java source files, 2 pom.xml files, 1 SPI services file, 1 Dockerfile, 1 docker-compose.yml, 1 frontend composable, and CHANGELOG.md) and performed a 6-item code quality review. I found **3 issues**: the Dockerfile references a jar file (`keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar`) that does not exist in the `docker/keycloak/` directory; the frontend `useAuth.js` hard-codes a production `auth.wotbtools.com` URL which prevents local development; and the `JuheQqIdentityProvider` logs `social_uid` length info that could be considered a minor information leak. The other known-good properties (APPKEY not hard-coded, no sensitive logging, JDK 21 HttpClient, final locals/params, error handling coverage, non-sensitive logging) are confirmed.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### EVIDENCE\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 1 — Sensitive information protection (APPKEY not hard-coded, not logged)**: CONFIRMED PASS. `JuheQqIdentityProviderConfig.java:21-22` — APPKEY is a configuration property retrieved via `getConfig().get(CONFIG_APPKEY)`, not hard-coded. `JuheQqIdentityProviderFactory.java:38` — `appkey.setSecret(true)` marks it as secret in Keycloak admin UI. `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:48-49` — on missing config, logs only \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"provider not fully configured\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", never the value. `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:82-83` and `149-151` — logs `code` and `type` only, never appkey or full URL.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 2 — JDK 21 java.net.http.HttpClient**: CONFIRMED PASS. `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:31-33` — uses `HttpClient.newBuilder()` with `connectTimeout`. `performLogin` at line 64-70 and `callback` at line 131-137 use `HttpRequest.newBuilder()` and `HTTP.send()`. Confirmed by `java/pom.xml:30` `<maven.compiler.release>21</maven.compiler.release>`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 3 — All local variables and method parameters use `final`**: CONFIRMED PASS. Every method parameter in all three Java files uses `final` (e.g., `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:37` constructor, :43 `performLogin`, :97 `callback`, :204 `encode`, :208 `isBlank`). All local variables use `final` (e.g., `appid`, `appkey`, `loginBaseUrl`, `callbackUrl`, `actLoginUrl`, `httpReq`, `httpResp`, `json`, `code`, `type`, `redirectUrl`, `nickname`, `faceimg`, etc.). Factory parameters and config constructor also use `final`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 4 — Error handling covers all spec-required scenarios**: CONFIRMED PASS. `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:48-53` — handles missing appid/appkey/loginBaseUrl in performLogin. `:72-75` — handles non-200 HTTP response in act=login. `:82-85` — handles API response code != 0, type != \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"qq\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", or empty redirect URL. `:90-93` — catches `IOException | InterruptedException` for network errors. `:104-112` — validates callback type=qq and non-empty code. `:120-123` — re-validates credentials in callback (defense-in-depth). `:139-142` — handles non-200 HTTP in callback. `:149-153` — validates callback response code/type/uid. `:187-189` — catches IO/InterruptedException in callback.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 5 — Logging only non-sensitive information**: CONFIRMED PASS with minor caveat. All log statements log only `code`, `type`, `nickname` (non-sensitive), and `social_uid` masked as `***` (line 151). However `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:150-151` logs `uid=%s` where the value is `(empty)` or `***` — this is fine. Also logs `nickname` at line 160 which is user-provided but not secret. **Minor risk**: logging `nickname` is acceptable but could contain user-provided special characters; no PII issue.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 6 — Configuration / deployment / integration integrity**: FOUND 3 PROBLEMS.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM A**: `docker/Dockerfile.keycloak:2` — `COPY docker/keycloak/keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar /opt/keycloak/providers/` references a file that does **not exist** in `docker/keycloak/`. The directory `docker/keycloak/` contains only `keycloak-social-provider-china-1.0.0.jar` and `wotbtools-realm.json`. The jar `keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar` is never built by any Dockerfile (the backend Dockerfile builds only `wotb-core` and `wotb-web`, not the keycloak provider module). **This Docker build will fail at `COPY` time.**\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM B**: `frontend/src/composables/useAuth.js:10-13` — The Keycloak URL is hard-coded to `https://auth.wotbtools.com`. This prevents local/offline development where Keycloak runs on `http://localhost:8080`. There is no environment variable or build-time configuration to override this.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM C**: `java/keycloak-juhe-qq-provider/pom.xml:43-47` — The `keycloak-services` dependency at scope `provided` is unusual; typically `keycloak-server-spi-private` is sufficient. However, since the code only references classes from `keycloak-server-spi` and `keycloak-server-spi-private` (no direct `keycloak-services` types), this is likely harmless but slightly over-broad.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### CHANGES\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nNone.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### RISKS\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Broken Docker build (docker/Dockerfile.keycloak:2)**: The `COPY` of `keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar` will fail because the jar is never built and does not exist in the source tree. **Mitigation**: Add a multi-stage build step in the Dockerfile to build the provider jar from source (similar to how `Dockerfile.backend` builds the backend), or pre-build and commit the jar, or modify the Dockerfile to reference the jar from the Maven build output.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Hard-coded production Keycloak URL (frontend/src/composables/useAuth.js:11)**: Local developers must manually edit this file to test against a local Keycloak instance. **Mitigation**: Use a build-time environment variable (e.g., Vite `import.meta.env.VITE_KEYCLOAK_URL`) with the production URL as default but overridable in `.env.development`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Unused keycloak-services dependency (pom.xml:43-47)**: While harmless at `provided` scope, it creates a minor maintenance burden and potential confusion about module boundaries. **Mitigation**: Remove if no direct code dependency exists, or add a comment explaining why it is needed.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Nickname logged at debug level (JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:160)**: `logger.debugf(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"juhe-qq: user info retrieved uid=*** nick=%s\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", nickname)` — logging the nickname is very low risk but could theoretically log user-provided content. **Mitigation**: Acceptable as-is since it's `debug` level and nickname is not secret, but add a comment acknowledging the choice.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### BLOCKERS\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\