itive information**: CONFIRMED PASS with minor caveat. All log statements log only `code`, `type`, `nickname` (non-sensitive), and `social_uid` masked as `***` (line 151). However `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:150-151` logs `uid=%s` where the value is `(empty)` or `***` — this is fine. Also logs `nickname` at line 160 which is user-provided but not secret. **Minor risk**: logging `nickname` is acceptable but could contain user-provided special characters; no PII issue.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 6 — Configuration / deployment / integration integrity**: FOUND 3 PROBLEMS.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM A**: `docker/Dockerfile.keycloak:2` — `COPY docker/keycloak/keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar /opt/keycloak/providers/` references a file that does **not exist** in `docker/keycloak/`. The directory `docker/keycloak/` contains only `keycloak-social-provider-china-1.0.0.jar` and `wotbtools-realm.json`. The jar `keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar` is never built by any Dockerfile (the backend Dockerfile builds only `wotb-core` and `wotb-web`, not the keycloak provider module). **This Docker build will fail at `COPY` time.**\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM B**: `frontend/src/composables/useAuth.js:10-13` — The Keycloak URL is hard-coded to `https://auth.wotbtools.com`. This prevents local/offline development where Keycloak runs on `http://localhost:8080`. There is no environment variable or build-time configuration to override this.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM C**: `java/keycloak-juhe-qq-provider/pom.xml:43-47` — The `keycloak-services` dependency at scope `provided` is unusual; typically `keycloak-server-spi-private` is sufficient. However, since the code only references classes from `keycloak-server-spi` and `keycloak-server-spi-private` (no direct `keycloak-services` types), this is likely harmless but slightly over-broad.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### CHANGES\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nNone.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### RISKS\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Broken Docker build (docker/Dockerfile.keycloak:2)**: The `COPY` of `keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar` will fail because the jar is never built and does not exist in the source tree. **Mitigation**: Add a multi-stage build step in the Dockerfile to build the provider jar from source (similar to how `Dockerfile.backend` builds the backend), or pre-build and commit the jar, or modify the Dockerfile to reference the jar from the Maven build output.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Hard-coded production Keycloak URL (frontend/src/composables/useAuth.js:11)**: Local developers must manually edit this file to test against a local Keycloak instance. **Mitigation**: Use a build-time environment variable (e.g., Vite `import.meta.env.VITE_KEYCLOAK_URL`) with the production URL as default but overridable in `.env.development`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Unused keycloak-services dependency (pom.xml:43-47)**: While harmless at `provided` scope, it creates a minor maintenance burden and potential confusion about module boundaries. **Mitigation**: Remove if no direct code dependency exists, or add a comment explaining why it is needed.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Nickname logged at debug level (JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:160)**: `logger.debugf(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"juhe-qq: user info retrieved uid=*** nick=%s\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", nickname)` — logging the nickname is very low risk but could theoretically log user-provided content. **Mitigation**: Acceptable as-is since it's `debug` level and nickname is not secret, but add a comment acknowledging the choice.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### BLOCKERS\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\