uptedException in callback.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 5 — Logging only non-sensitive information**: CONFIRMED PASS with minor caveat. All log statements log only `code`, `type`, `nickname` (non-sensitive), and `social_uid` masked as `***` (line 151). However `JuheQqIdentityProvider.java:150-151` logs `uid=%s` where the value is `(empty)` or `***` — this is fine. Also logs `nickname` at line 160 which is user-provided but not secret. **Minor risk**: logging `nickname` is acceptable but could contain user-provided special characters; no PII issue.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Item 6 — Configuration / deployment / integration integrity**: FOUND 3 PROBLEMS.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM A**: `docker/Dockerfile.keycloak:2` — `COPY docker/keycloak/keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar /opt/keycloak/providers/` references a file that does **not exist** in `docker/keycloak/`. The directory `docker/keycloak/` contains only `keycloak-social-provider-china-1.0.0.jar` and `wotbtools-realm.json`. The jar `keycloak-juhe-qq-provider.jar` is never built by any Dockerfile (the backend Dockerfile builds only `wotb-core` and `wotb-web`, not the keycloak provider module). **This Docker build will fail at `COPY` time.**\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM B**: `frontend/src/composables/useAuth.js:10-13` — The Keycloak URL is hard-coded to `https://auth.wotbtools.com`. This prevents local/offline development where Keycloak runs on `http://localhost:8080`. There is no environment variable or build-time configuration to override this.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  - **PROBLEM C**: `java/keycloak-juhe-qq-provider/pom.xml:43-47` — The `keycloak-services` dependency at scope `provided` is unusual; typically `keycloak-server-spi-private` is sufficient. However, since the code only references classes from `keycloak-server-spi` and `keycloak-server-spi-private` (no direct `keycloak-services` types), this is likely harmless but slightly over-broad.\\\\\